body:
A few comments on that issue.

1. It is futile to override the Content-Type header this way: it is overridden by the client runtime based on the "consumes" mime types
2. Everything works just fine if the operation declares only one "consumes": "multipart/form-data" (see a working example: https://github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/tree/master/examples/file-server)
3. The problem comes from the two "consumes" types specified:
   * problem N°1: the order of the mime types for the client is reversed. So it picks primarily "application/x-www-form-urlencoded", which was not intended
   * problem N°2: although the swagger 2.0 states that files _may_ be transferred over "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" ([reference](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification/blob/main/versions/2.0.md#parameter-object)), our client runtime (go-openapi/runtime/client) does not support that (because it is not the _preferred_ way) and results in a mismatch: sending a multipart body with Content-Type: "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"

It is possible to work around this problem by forcing the MIME type in the operation by using an option.
Like so:
```go
dummyAuth := runtime.ClientAuthInfoWriterFunc(func(_ runtime.ClientRequest, _ strfmt.Registry) error {
		return nil
	})
forceMime := func(mime string) my_tag.ClientOption {
		return func(r *runtime.ClientOperation) {
			r.ConsumesMediaTypes = []string{mime}
		}
	}

const content = "content of this file"
rdr := strings.NewReader(content)
params := my_tag.NewOperationNameParams().
				WithFile(runtime.NamedReader("file", rdr))
resp, err := c.MyTag.OperationName(params, dummyAuth, forceMime("multipart/form-data"))
````
